3.6.0 — Constitutional Purpose
This section encodes the external legal frameworks that define what travelers are owed by law — independent of any insurance policy, credit card benefit, or airline contract they personally hold. These are the statutory floors: rights that exist whether or not the traveler knows about them, whether or not they are mentioned in any document the platform has ingested, and whether or not any provider acknowledges them.

The platform's core promise is to help travelers understand their full recovery picture. That promise is incomplete if the platform can only read the traveler's own documents. A traveler whose policy is weak or absent still has statutory rights. A traveler whose carrier is denying an EU obligation still has statutory rights. The platform must be able to surface those rights deterministically — not as AI-generated opinion, but as encoded rule tables derived from binding law.

Section 3.6 defines three things: (1) the statutory rights rule tables, (2) how those rights connect to the Coverage Graph as a special node type, and (3) the Disruption Resolution State Machine — the formalized sequence of states a traveler moves through from the moment a disruption is suspected to the moment a claim outcome is recorded.

BINDING INVARIANT
Statutory rights are encoded as deterministic lookup tables. They are never AI-generated, never approximated, and never omitted because a traveler's documents don't mention them. If a disruption occurs in a statutory jurisdiction, the applicable rights are surfaced regardless of what the traveler's policy says.

3.6.1 — What This Section Is Not
This section does not provide legal advice. It does not guarantee any outcome. It does not tell a traveler they will receive compensation. It encodes what the law says travelers are entitled to ask for — not what any specific airline, insurer, or adjudicator will actually pay.

⛔ PROHIBITED LANGUAGE — Never surface to travelers
•"You are entitled to €400 in compensation" — asserting certainty about what will be paid
•"The airline must pay you" — directive language about carrier behavior
•"You will receive this amount" — outcome prediction
•"File immediately — you have rights" — pressure language
•"The law requires the airline to compensate you" — legal advice framing

✓ APPROVED LANGUAGE — Use these patterns
•"EU passenger rights regulations may apply to this disruption. Under EU261, delays of this type and distance are typically associated with compensation of €[amount]. Whether it applies to your specific situation depends on factors including the cause of the delay."
•"Based on the route and delay duration, EU passenger rights regulations appear relevant. Here's what those rights typically cover — and what you'd need to document."
•"Your disruption happened at a US airport. DOT rules set minimum compensation for denied boarding on domestic flights. Here's what those rules say."

3.6.2 — Statutory Frameworks Encoded
The following frameworks are encoded as deterministic rule tables in this section. Each framework covers a specific jurisdiction and disruption type. The platform evaluates applicability based on route, origin/destination airports, carrier registration, and disruption type — all of which are available from the incident and itinerary data.

Framework	Jurisdiction	Disruption Types Covered	Key Triggers	FAM Code
