The platform encodes these four frameworks at MVP. Additional frameworks (Canadian APPR, Australian Consumer Law aviation provisions, ASEAN Open Skies protections) are noted as Phase 2 additions. The table structure is designed to be extensible — adding a new jurisdiction is an INSERT, not an architecture change.

3.6.3 — EU Regulation 261/2004 Rule Table
EU261 applies when: (a) the flight departs from an EU/EEA airport (regardless of carrier), OR (b) the flight arrives at an EU/EEA airport on an EU/EEA-registered carrier. This is the platform's EU261 jurisdiction check — evaluated from the disrupted route segment's origin and destination airports plus the operating carrier's registration country.

3.6.3.A — Compensation Tiers (Article 7)
Flight Distance	Delay Threshold	Compensation Amount	Notes
Up to 1,500 km	3 hours or more at final destination	€250 per passenger	Covers most intra-EU short-haul routes
1,500–3,500 km (intra-EU 3,500+ km)	3 hours or more at final destination	€400 per passenger	Covers medium-haul intra-EU and some intercontinental
Over 3,500 km (non-intra-EU)	3–4 hours at final destination	€300 per passenger (50% reduction applies)	4+ hours = full €600
Over 3,500 km (non-intra-EU)	4 hours or more at final destination	€600 per passenger	Long-haul intercontinental routes

DISTANCE CALCULATION RULE
Distance is measured as the great-circle distance between the first departure airport of the booking and the final destination. For connecting flights where a missed connection caused the delay, the full journey distance applies, not just the disrupted leg.

3.6.3.B — Extraordinary Circumstances (Article 5(3)) — The Compensation Exception
Carriers are not required to pay Article 7 compensation if the cancellation or delay was caused by extraordinary circumstances that could not have been avoided even if all reasonable measures had been taken. This is the most commonly disputed aspect of EU261.

Circumstance	Extraordinary?	Platform Framing
Severe weather (genuine — not mild)	Generally YES	"The airline may claim extraordinary circumstances. Weather-related claims are frequently disputed. Document the official weather conditions."
Air Traffic Control restrictions	Generally YES	"ATC restrictions are typically considered extraordinary. The airline may use this to reduce compensation obligation."
Strike by external staff (airport, ATC)	Generally YES	"External strikes outside the airline's control are typically extraordinary. Airline staff strikes are not."
Airline staff strike	Generally NO	"Airline staff strikes are generally not considered extraordinary. Compensation rights may still apply."
Technical/mechanical fault	Generally NO	"Technical faults are generally part of normal airline operations and not extraordinary. Compensation rights typically apply."
Hidden manufacturing defect (rare)	Possibly YES	"This is a contested area. Document the airline's stated reason and the specific fault."
COVID/pandemic government restriction	Context-dependent	"Government restrictions may qualify as extraordinary in some circumstances. Document any government orders."

3.6.3.C — Right to Care (Article 9)
Regardless of extraordinary circumstances — even when compensation is not owed — airlines have a duty of care obligation. These rights apply whenever a delay is expected to be 2 hours or more:

Delay Duration	Right to Care Entitlements
2 hours or more (short-haul, up to 1,500 km)	Meals and refreshments proportional to waiting time. Two telephone calls, emails, or faxes.
3 hours or more (medium-haul, 1,500–3,500 km)	Same as above.
4 hours or more (long-haul, over 3,500 km)	Same as above.
Overnight delay (any duration)	Hotel accommodation. Transport between airport and hotel. All of the above.

DUTY OF CARE IS NOT EXTRAORDINARY
Right to care under Article 9 applies even when the airline successfully claims extraordinary circumstances and does not owe compensation under Article 7. These are independent obligations. The platform surfaces both separately.

3.6.3.D — Right to Reimbursement or Rerouting (Article 8)
Right	Trigger	What It Means
Full refund	Cancellation or delay of 5+ hours and traveler chooses not to travel	Reimbursement of ticket cost within 7 days. Return flight to first departure point if already mid-journey.
Rerouting at earliest opportunity	Cancellation or delay and traveler wants to travel	Alternative transport to final destination under comparable conditions, at earliest opportunity.
Rerouting at later date	Cancellation or delay and traveler wants to travel but not immediately	Alternative transport at a later date of the traveler's choosing, subject to availability.

3.6.3.E — Denied Boarding (Article 4)
Involuntary denied boarding due to overbooking triggers immediate compensation at the Article 7 tiers. The airline must first seek volunteers before denying boarding to unwilling passengers. If a passenger is involuntarily denied boarding, compensation is due at departure — not after arrival.

