3.6.4 — US DOT Rules
US DOT rules apply to flights that depart from a US airport — for all carriers, domestic and international. They do not apply to inbound international flights on foreign carriers. Two distinct rule sets apply: the denied boarding compensation matrix and the 2024 refund rule for cancellations and significant changes.

3.6.4.A — Denied Boarding Compensation (14 CFR Part 250)
When a passenger is involuntarily denied boarding due to oversales on a domestic or international flight departing the US, the carrier must offer compensation. The amount depends on the delay to the passenger's final destination.

Delay to Final Destination	Domestic Flight Compensation	International Flight Compensation	Maximum
1–2 hours (domestic) / 1–4 hours (international)	200% of one-way fare, minimum $775	200% of one-way fare, minimum $775	$775 minimum
Over 2 hours (domestic) / over 4 hours (international)	400% of one-way fare, minimum $1,550	400% of one-way fare, minimum $1,550	$1,550 minimum
No delay (carrier arranges comparable flight)	No compensation required	No compensation required	—

Compensation must be paid in cash or check. The airline may offer vouchers but the passenger has the right to demand cash. This right must be offered and disclosed at the gate.

3.6.4.B — 2024 DOT Refund Rule (Effective October 2024)
Under the 2024 DOT rule, airlines must provide automatic cash refunds (without requiring passengers to request them) for:
•Cancelled flights — regardless of reason
•Significant changes to domestic flights: departure or arrival time change of 3 or more hours; departure or arrival airport change; increase in number of connections; downgrade to lower class of service; connecting airports in different cities; connections requiring significantly longer travel
•Significant changes to international flights: departure or arrival time change of 6 or more hours
•Significant baggage delays: checked baggage not delivered within 12 hours of domestic flight arrival or 15-30 hours of international flight arrival

REFUND MUST BE CASH
Under the 2024 DOT rule, refunds must be in the original form of payment (cash, credit card, etc.). Airlines cannot substitute vouchers or travel credits unless the passenger affirmatively chooses them. The platform surfaces this distinction — accepting a voucher instead of a cash refund is a choice with consequences for downstream coverage claims.

3.6.4.C — Enforcement Path (US)
Travelers file complaints with the DOT Aviation Consumer Protection Division. The DOT enforces these rules against carriers operating in the US. Airlines are required to post their customer service plans and comply with them. Third-party enforcement through small claims court is also available for individual claims.

3.6.5 — Montreal Convention 1999 (Articles 19 & 22)
The Montreal Convention applies to international air transportation between countries that have ratified it — currently 190+ countries including all EU member states, the US, UK, Canada, and most major aviation markets. It establishes liability limits for delay, baggage loss, baggage damage, and baggage delay.

3.6.5.A — Delay Liability (Article 19)
Under Article 19, the carrier is liable for damage caused by delay in the carriage of passengers, baggage, or cargo. The carrier can avoid liability by proving it took all reasonable measures, or that it was impossible to take such measures. Liability is not automatic — the passenger must demonstrate they suffered actual damage from the delay.

3.6.5.B — Liability Limits (Article 22) — SDR Values
Montreal Convention limits are expressed in Special Drawing Rights (SDRs) — an international monetary unit whose value fluctuates. The platform uses current SDR-to-currency conversion rates where displayed. Limits are per passenger.

Category	SDR Limit	Approximate USD (2024)	Notes
Passenger delay	4,694 SDR	~$6,200	Maximum recoverable for proven delay damages. Not automatic — must prove loss.
Checked baggage loss/damage/delay	1,288 SDR	~$1,700	Per passenger. Carrier can prove baggage was defective to reduce liability.
Carry-on baggage	1,288 SDR	~$1,700	Only if carrier at fault.
Higher declared value	Unlimited (passenger declares value)	N/A	Passenger can declare higher value at check-in for additional fee. Carrier liable up to declared value.

SDR CONVERSION NOTE
SDR values are updated annually. The platform displays approximate local currency values with the notation: "Based on current SDR conversion rates — verify with your carrier or legal advisor for the precise current value." The platform never asserts a fixed cash value for Montreal Convention limits.

3.6.5.C — Relationship to EU261
EU261 and the Montreal Convention can both apply to the same disruption. They cover different things: EU261 provides fixed compensation for the disruption itself (standardised, no proof of loss required for Article 7 compensation). The Montreal Convention provides liability for proven consequential damage from delay. They are complementary — filing under both is possible and in many cases appropriate. The platform surfaces both where applicable and explains they are independent claims to independent recipients.

3.6.6 — UK Regulation EC 261/2004 (Retained Law)
Post-Brexit, the UK retained EU Regulation 261/2004 as domestic law. The substantive rights are identical to EU261 for flights departing UK airports or arriving at UK airports on UK-registered carriers. Key difference: enforcement is through UK bodies (CAA, ADR schemes) rather than EU NEBs. Compensation amounts remain in pounds sterling at parity with the Euro amounts (£250/£400/£600).

For a flight disrupted at Heathrow: UK retained law applies for the departure. For the same traveler's onward EU flight disrupted at a French airport: EU261 applies. Both may apply to the same journey and the platform surfaces them as separate but related claims.

3.6.7 — Statutory Coverage Node in the Coverage Graph
Section 3.3 defines the Coverage Graph as a set of CoverageNodes — each representing one coverage source. Prior to this section, the only valid source types were: travel_insurance, credit_card_benefit, airline_obligation, home_renters, warranty. This section adds a new source type: statutory_right.

NEW SOURCE TYPE
A CoverageNode with source_type = 'statutory_right' represents a right the traveler holds by law — not by contract, not by policy, and not by benefit guide. It cannot be waived by policy language, cannot be excluded by a carrier's terms, and cannot be superseded by any contractual node. It is a floor, not a ceiling.

