primacy_type	statutory	primary | secondary | tertiary | unknown	Statutory nodes are always evaluated before contractual nodes
can_be_waived	false (hard rule)	true (policy-dependent)	Statutory rights cannot be contractually waived
requires_policy_document	false	true	Statutory nodes are generated from rule tables, not uploaded documents
jurisdiction_code	ISO 3166-1 code (e.g., EU261, US-DOT)	From governing_jurisdiction on PolicyVersion	Indicates which statutory framework applies
framework_version	e.g., EU261-2004, US-DOT-2024	N/A	Version of the statutory framework encoded
confidence_label	HIGH_STRUCTURAL_ALIGNMENT if jurisdiction confirmed; CONDITIONAL if uncertain	Per Section 9.2	Jurisdiction confirmation is the key determinant

3.6.7.B — How Statutory Nodes Are Generated
Statutory nodes are not extracted from documents. They are generated by the Coverage Graph engine when:
•The disrupted route segment's origin or destination airport is in a statutory jurisdiction (EU/EEA, UK, US)
•The disruption type matches a type covered by that jurisdiction's framework (delay, cancellation, denied boarding)
•The cause classification from the CCO is not definitively extraordinary circumstances (if UNKNOWN: dual-branch — statutory node generated with conditional confidence)

The trigger is the route + disruption type combination. No document upload required. No policy attachment required. A traveler with no policies attached and no credit card benefits linked still gets statutory nodes if their disruption qualifies.

3.6.7.C — Statutory Node Display Rules
Scenario	Display Behavior
Jurisdiction confirmed, cause not extraordinary	Show statutory node with HIGH confidence. Display applicable rights. Display enforcement path.
Jurisdiction confirmed, cause claimed extraordinary by carrier	Show statutory node with CONDITIONAL confidence. Note: "The airline may claim an exemption. Document the cause carefully."
Jurisdiction confirmed, cause UNKNOWN (CCO dual-branch)	Show statutory node on both branches. Note: "Whether these rights apply may depend on the confirmed cause of the disruption."
Route crosses multiple jurisdictions (e.g., JFK → LHR → CDG)	Show statutory nodes for each applicable jurisdiction on the disrupted leg. Explain they are independent.
Jurisdiction not covered by any encoded framework	No statutory node generated. Display: "No statutory passenger rights framework has been encoded for this route. Check with local consumer protection authorities."

3.6.8 — Acceptance / Voucher / Refund Consequence Matrix
This is the engine behind the advisory logic in Section 3.3.19.A (Voucher Acceptance Doctrine). That section defines the language and posture. This section defines the consequence logic: what each acceptance type does to each coverage path.

ADVISORY ONLY — NO BLOCKING
The platform uses this matrix to inform the traveler of consequences before they act. It never blocks an acceptance. The traveler always has the right to accept any offer from any carrier at any time. The platform's role is to make consequences visible — not to prevent choices.

Acceptance Type	Statutory Rights (EU261/DOT)	Credit Card Benefit	Travel Insurance	Guidance Trigger
Full cash refund accepted	Statutory claim path closes (carrier has refunded). Right to care/duty of care docs still valuable for consequential damage claims.	Trip interruption: carrier refund reduces reimbursable loss. Claim still possible for out-of-pocket expenses above refund.	Trip cancellation: carrier refund reduces insurable loss. Policy may still cover non-refundable costs.	"You received a refund. Your coverage may still apply to additional expenses beyond what the airline refunded."
Voucher accepted (future flight credit)	Statutory cash refund right may be waived by acceptance. Compensation right (EU261 Article 7) is separate and not extinguished by voucher acceptance.	Depends on card benefit terms. Many cards treat voucher acceptance as partial resolution. Document voucher value.	Depends on policy language. 'Accepted voucher' is an acceptance event — may affect loss calculation.	"Before accepting a voucher, know that your right to a cash refund and your EU261 compensation right are two separate things. A voucher covers one but may not cover the other."
