3.6.11 — Behavioral Invariants
ID	Rule
I-01	Statutory rights are surfaced based on route and disruption type — never based on what documents the traveler has uploaded. No document is required to generate a statutory node.
I-02	A statutory CoverageNode with source_type = 'statutory_right' is always evaluated before any contractual node. It cannot be suppressed by policy language or benefit guide terms.
I-03	The platform never asserts that a traveler will receive statutory compensation. It surfaces what the law says travelers are entitled to ask for and what they need to document.
I-04	Extraordinary circumstances is always surfaced as a caveat on EU261 compensation claims. It is never omitted. The traveler must understand compensation can be contested.
I-05	The Consequence Matrix is surfaced at OFFER_RECEIVED state — before the traveler accepts or declines. It is never surfaced for the first time after acceptance.
I-06	Duty of care (EU261 Article 9) is surfaced independently of compensation (Article 7). They are presented as separate obligations, not bundled.
I-07	Filing deadlines are surfaced at ROUTING_DETERMINED and remain visible until the deadline passes or the claim is filed. They are never hidden.
I-08	The DOT 2024 cash refund right is surfaced for all cancellations and significant changes on US-departing flights. The distinction between cash refund and voucher is always made explicit.
I-09	Evidence capture is parallel — it runs from DISRUPTION_CONFIRMED regardless of which resolution state the traveler is in. It does not wait for routing to be determined.
I-10	All disruption resolution state transitions emit events to the event ledger. The complete resolution journey is always replayable from the ledger.

